{% block content %}
  <h2>First entry: Second Sons Canada</h2>

  <h3>What the reporting establishes about the group</h3>
  <p>Second Sons Canada is a men's-only, members-only organization founded in 2024. The Canadian Anti-Hate Network, CBC News, and an internal Public Safety Canada briefing describe it as a white-nationalist group and the militant arm of the network founded by Jeremy MacKenzie, who also founded Diagolon (CBC, December 2025; Canadian Anti-Hate Network, October 2025). Public Safety Canada's briefing, obtained by CBC, warns the broader "active club" movement poses a risk for "extreme violence" and states Second Sons has more than 15 chapters across Canada (CBC, on the Public Safety Canada brief).</p>
  <p>The group presents itself publicly as a fitness and "nationalist" fraternal club. CBC's visual-investigations unit reviewed the leaders' own podcasts and livestreams and reported that they express pro-Nazi views, describe a violent "race war," and call for the mass deportation of non-white people; the Canadian Anti-Hate Network describes the group's stated goal of "remigration" as a euphemism for ethnic cleansing (CBC, December 2025; Canadian Anti-Hate Network, October 2025). We relay these as the findings of those organizations.</p>

  <h3>What it has done in the territory</h3>
  <p>Second Sons has been active in Robinson Huron Treaty territory and the surrounding region over the past year:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Cochrane, winter 2025-26: members attended a community Highway 11 safety rally and raised a sign blaming newly immigrated truck drivers for highway deaths. Cochrane's mayor said a member approached him and secretly recorded the conversation, and that the footage was later edited (CBC News, Northern Ontario).</li>
    <li>Sudbury, late May 2026: roughly ten masked members marched through downtown and installed a cross reading "silent slaughter" at the Crosses for Change opioid-overdose memorial, filming a promotional video that blamed "foreigners" for the opioid crisis. The cross was later removed (CBC News and Sudbury.com).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Researchers told CBC the pattern is to attach the group to real local crises (highway deaths, the opioid crisis, homelessness) to gain attention and recruit. A former extremist interviewed by CBC called this "mainstreaming," and a researcher at Ontario Tech University's Centre on Hate, Bias and Extremism described the group as "capitalizing on local social issues to recruit" (CBC News, Northern Ontario).</p>

  <h3>What the record says about the threat to First Nations</h3>
  <p>We want to be accurate rather than alarming. On the public record, the group's most explicit, named hatred is directed at immigrants and newcomers, not First Nations; we found no documented statement by its leaders targeting First Nations, treaties, or Indigenous land by name, and no documented incident of the group targeting a specific First Nation. We say that plainly so no one overstates it.</p>
  <p>At the same time, the concern for members is real and rests on documented facts: the group is organizing inside this territory now; its leaders, by CBC's account, train for what they themselves call a "race war"; its ideology asserts a white "birthright" to land that is treaty and, in places, unceded territory; and the broader far-right movement it belongs to has a documented record of anti-Indigenous harassment and violence in Canada (for example, the surge in anti-Indigenous threats during the 2020 Wet'suwet'en solidarity protests, documented by the Canadian Anti-Hate Network and reported by CBC). The honest summary is "present and growing," not "currently targeting us."</p>

  <h3>Questions a member or community can ask</h3>
  <p>In the spirit of the rest of this hub, the useful response is questions, not fear:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Has our Chief and Council, or our community safety lead, been briefed by police on this group's presence in the area?</li>
    <li>If members of this group approach our members, attend a community event, or appear at a local rally, what is our plan, and who do people contact?</li>
    <li>Are our local councils and event organizers aware of the tactic of attaching to a real local issue (highway safety, the opioid crisis) and recording officials?</li>
    <li>What local supports exist if a member experiences harassment or intimidation?</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>How others have responded</h3>
  <p>Northern Ontario politicians have condemned the group's visits. Sudbury's mayor said there is "no place in Greater Sudbury for hate, white supremacist ideology, or attempts to scapegoat newcomers" (CBC News and Sudbury.com). Police have noted the group is not itself illegal but that they watch for incitement of violence against an identifiable group and would act if conduct crossed into criminality (Greater Sudbury Police, via CBC). Neither Second Sons nor Diagolon is a listed terrorist entity in Canada, though there have been public calls for such a designation (Public Safety Canada listed-entities page; Global News).</p>

